  "verdict": "VALID_VULNERABILITY",
  "defense": "The claim is completely accurate. The contract functions as a library but leaves its initialization functions (`initWallet` and `initMultiowned`) publicly accessible. Because the library's own storage is uninitialized upon deployment (`m_numOwners == 0`), any user can call `initWallet` directly on the library contract to make themselves the owner. Once they are the owner, they can call the `kill()` function, which executes `suicide()` (selfdestruct) and destroys the library. This exact vulnerability was responsible for the Parity multi-sig wallet freeze.",
  "evidence": "modifier only_uninitialized { if (m_numOwners > 0) throw; _; }\n\nfunction initWallet(address[] _owners, uint _required, uint _daylimit) only_uninitialized {\n  initDaylimit(_daylimit);\n  initMultiowned(_owners, _required);\n}\n\nfunction kill(address _to) onlymanyowners(sha3(msg.data)) external {\n  suicide(_to);\n}",
